text:
Flushing Meadow Park (Queens): The corona dumps and an ash butte, seen from the vicinity of 55th Avenue and 111th Street. This area later became part of the New York World's Fair of 1939-40, where some of the industrial exhibits were erected.

P.L. Sperr

October 2, 1935
Views 1,2,3

Views 1,2,3

111th Street, south from 55th Avenue. The street is being widened as part of the approach to the World's Fair grounds. The extensive Fair grounds are on the left, part of Flushing Meadow Park.

P. L. Sperr

May 30, 1938

Flushing Meadow Park (Queens): The Maritime Building at the New York World's Fair 1939-40. The twin prows rise eighty feet. The architects are Ely Jacques Kahn and Muschenheim and Brounn. View 2 is across a parking space on the east side of 111th Street and 55th Avenue.

View 1: May 29, 1939
View 2: June 23, 1940 Neg. # 2381

P. L. Sperr
title: Queens: Flushing Meadow Park - New York World's Fair of 1939-40 - [Maritime Agency building.]
